- The $1.1 billion “contingent‑consideration reversal” recorded for the Auris Health acquisition was shown in the Medical‑Devices segment as a **$1.1 billion gain** (see JNJ 10‑K p. 89).  In the cash‑flow statement it appears as a **non‑cash adjustment** that is subtracted from operating cash flow (see JNJ 10‑K p. 51), meaning the gain lifted segment earnings but did **not add cash** to the balance sheet.  Consequently, the reversal improved reported profitability and gave J&J more “paper” flexibility to fund future R&D or acquisitions, but it did not directly increase liquidity or borrowing capacity.

- CVS’s own point‑of‑care and health‑service offerings that sit in the same market space are described in its 10‑K (pages 4‑8):  
  • **MinuteClinic and HealthHUB walk‑in medical clinics** that provide primary‑care, chronic‑disease management and on‑site diagnostics;  
  • **Aetna Virtual Primary Care** and other tele‑health services;  
  • **COVID‑19 testing and vaccination sites** (large‑scale retail‑based diagnostic services).  

These CVS services could **complement J&J’s Medical‑Devices strategy** by serving as distribution or adoption channels for J&J’s surgical and interventional devices in community‑based settings.  At the same time, if CVS expands its clinic capabilities into procedural or minimally‑invasive care, those offerings could **constrain J&J’s positioning** by creating a competing venue for the same procedures that currently occur in hospitals and specialty centers.
